{
  "answer": "**The second couplet (sher) after the matla (opening couplet) in chapter 168 of *Diwan-e-Ghalib* reads as follows.**\n\n**Original (Urdu script):**  \nبے_در_و_دیوار سا اک گھر بنایا چاہیے  \nکوئی ہمسایہ نہ ہو اور پاسباں کوئی نہ ہو.[^1]\n\n**Transliteration:**  \nBe-dar-o-deewar sa ek ghar banaya chahiye  \nKoi humsaya na ho aur pasban koi na ho.[^2]\n\n**Translation:**  \nA house I'll build of neither wall nor stone,  \nNo neighbor there, no guard, and be alone.[^3]\n\nThis ghazal expresses a desire for utter solitude, and this couplet continues the theme by envisioning an open, unguarded shelter free from neighbors or watchmen.[^4]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, [paragraph](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/168-rahiye-ab-aisi-jagah-chal-kar-jahan-koi-na-ho/original/#p-a28967).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, chapter 168, transliteration (as rendered in the corpus; note: verse lacks discrete paragraph marker in this variant).[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E",
